{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513661"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12188"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12188"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.1,0.59,0.06,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70583"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12188"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56047"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"272"},{"type":"tags","id":"2245"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4632"},{"type":"tags","id":"5595"},{"type":"tags","id":"5613"},{"type":"tags","id":"5615"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7409"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23699"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70583"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman presents to hospital for an open reduction and internal fixation of a complete fracture of the left radius and ulna. The procedure is performed under brachial plexus block with a supraclavicular approach. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The intraoperative course is uneventful, but in the recovery ward she complains of increasing breathlessness, light-headedness, and a metallic taste in her mouth. On examination, she appears distressed and anxious. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 135/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are decreased breath sounds and hyper-resonance to percussion on the left side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for her current condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary embolism","Atelectasis","Pneumothorax","Hemi-diaphragmatic paralysis","Local anaesthetic systemic toxicity"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of iatrogenic pneumothorax following supraclavicular brachial plexus block. \u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most common complications of this approach due to the proximity of the pleura to the injection site. While the risk has decreased with ultrasound guidance, the classic findings of unilateral decreased breath sounds and hyperresonance to percussion strongly suggest this diagnosis. The anxiety and light-headedness can be explained by hypoxia and respiratory distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with sudden onset dyspnoea, pleuritic chest pain, and tachycardia. While possible after surgery, it would be unusual this early in the post-operative period and would not cause unilateral decreased breath sounds with hyperresonance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtelectasis\u003C/strong\u003E would cause decreased breath sounds but would be associated with dull percussion note rather than hyperresonance. It typically occurs in dependent regions of the lung and is not usually associated with significant respiratory distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHemi-diaphragmatic paralysis\u003C/strong\u003E can occur due to phrenic nerve blockade during brachial plexus block. However, it typically causes dull percussion note rather than hyperresonance, and most patients without underlying lung disease remain asymptomatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocal anaesthetic systemic toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a characteristic progression of symptoms: initial perioral numbness, metallic taste, and tongue paraesthesia, followed by confusion, seizures, and ultimately cardiovascular collapse. While the patient has a metallic taste and anxiety, the presence of unilateral decreased breath sounds and hyperresonance is more consistent with pneumothorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of iatrogenic pneumothorax depends on its size and the patient\u0027s symptoms. Small, asymptomatic pneumothoraces may be managed conservatively, while larger or symptomatic ones require needle decompression or chest tube insertion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pneumothorax is a common complication of supraclavicular brachial plexus block due to the proximity of the pleura","Pneumothorax typically presents within 24 hours with respiratory distress, decreased breath sounds, and hyperresonance to percussion","Local anaesthetic systemic toxicity presents with perioral tingling, metallic taste, seizures, and cardiovascular collapse"],"references":["Woolley EJ et al. Neurological sequelae of brachial plexus nerve block. Ann Surg. 1959:149:53-60"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56047"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12188"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56047"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T21:58:13+10:30","updatedAt":"20